<html>
<head>
<title>3.1 Converting ERD to Tables</title>
<style>
table { border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; margin-bottom: 20px; }
th, td { border: 1px solid black; padding: 8px; text-align: left; }
th { background-color: #f2f2f2; }
h2 { color: #333; }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>3.1 Converting ERD to Tables</h1>
<p>Based on the Entity Diagram, the following tables are derived for the Invisible-Chat system. Since the current implementation uses local storage (IndexedDB) and no server-side database, these are conceptual tables that could be used for a full database implementation.</p>

<h2>1. User Table</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Column Name</th><th>Data Type</th><th>Constraints</th><th>Description</th></tr>
<tr><td>userId</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td>PRIMARY KEY, NOT NULL</td><td>Unique identifier for the user</td></tr>
<tr><td>username</td><td>VARCHAR(100)</td><td>NOT NULL</td><td>Display name of the user</td></tr>
<tr><td>secretKey</td><td>VARCHAR(255)</td><td>NOT NULL</td><td>Encryption key for messages</td></tr>
<tr><td>currentRoom</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td></td><td>Last active room</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>2. Message Table</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Column Name</th><th>Data Type</th><th>Constraints</th><th>Description</th></tr>
<tr><td>messageId</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td>PRIMARY KEY, NOT NULL</td><td>Unique identifier for the message</td></tr>
<tr><td>sender</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td>FOREIGN KEY (User.userId), NOT NULL</td><td>User who sent the message</td></tr>
<tr><td>room</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td>FOREIGN KEY (Room.roomName), NOT NULL</td><td>Room where message was sent</td></tr>
<tr><td>imageData</td><td>TEXT</td><td>NOT NULL</td><td>Base64 encoded steganographic image</td></tr>
<tr><td>encryptedContent</td><td>TEXT</td><td></td><td>Encrypted text hidden in image</td></tr>
<tr><td>timestamp</td><td>DATETIME</td><td>NOT NULL</td><td>When the message was sent</td></tr>
<tr><td>isDecoded</td><td>BOOLEAN</td><td>DEFAULT FALSE</td><td>Whether the message has been decoded locally</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>3. Room Table</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Column Name</th><th>Data Type</th><th>Constraints</th><th>Description</th></tr>
<tr><td>roomName</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td>PRIMARY KEY, NOT NULL</td><td>Unique name of the room</td></tr>
<tr><td>description</td><td>VARCHAR(255)</td><td></td><td>Description of the room</td></tr>
<tr><td>createdAt</td><td>DATETIME</td><td>NOT NULL</td><td>When the room was created</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>4. Settings Table</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Column Name</th><th>Data Type</th><th>Constraints</th><th>Description</th></tr>
<tr><td>settingId</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td>PRIMARY KEY, NOT NULL</td><td>Unique identifier for the setting</td></tr>
<tr><td>userId</td><td>VARCHAR(50)</td><td>FOREIGN KEY (User.userId), NOT NULL</td><td>User this setting belongs to</td></tr>
<tr><td>settingKey</td><td>VARCHAR(100)</td><td>NOT NULL</td><td>Name of the setting</td></tr>
<tr><td>settingValue</td><td>VARCHAR(255)</td><td>NOT NULL</td><td>Value of the setting</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Relationships</h2>
<ul>
<li>User (1) -- (many) Message: One user can send multiple messages</li>
<li>Room (1) -- (many) Message: One room can contain multiple messages</li>
<li>User (1) -- (1) Settings: One user has one settings record (conceptually, but settings table allows multiple per user)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Note:</strong> In the current implementation, messages are stored locally in IndexedDB without server-side persistence. The tables above represent a potential database schema for a full server-backed implementation.</p>
</body>
</html>
